					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">In fact with a mapper that trigger an IRQ at a very predictable PPU clock (such as MMC3 or MMC5 but NOT any VRC series, FDS, N106, etc...) it could use the double interrupt method :
<br />
<br />Interrupt 1 prepare field for interrupt 2 the next scanline, and then go into a long string of nops, that are interrupted by interupt 2. Inside interrupt 2 you get 2 cycle error (which is 6 pixels NTSC and 6.4 (7 ?) pixels PAL, both fitting into 1 tile if you're lucky).
<br />
<br />I know they managed to somehow kill that remaining 1-cycle jitter on the C64 (which has a built-in scanline counter that can both trigger IRQs and be read at any time), however I don't know if that could be possible on NES. Maybe rely on obscure $2007 read behavior ?</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
